{"title_page": "Philippe Bodson", "text_new": "'''Philippe Andr\u00e9 Eug\u00e8ne, Baron Bodson''' (born 1944 - passed away 4/4/2020) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] businessman.\n\n==Education==\nHe graduated as civil engineer at the [[University of Li\u00e8ge]] (ULg) and obtained a Master of Business Administration at [[INSEAD]] ([[Fontainebleau]], France)\n\n==Career==\nHe started his career at [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] in [[Paris]] where he worked for three years. He then worked for four years for the [[Daus Bank]] in Germany and the United States. In 1977, he started working for [[Glaverbel]], where he would be the [[CEO]] from 1980 until 1989. From September 1989 until December 1998, he was a non-executive member of the board of directors of [[Fortis (finance)|Fortis]]. From 1999 until 2003, he was a [[senator]] in the [[Belgian Senate]] for the [[Mouvement reformateur]]. , From 2004 until 2010, he was a Director at Fortis From 2004 until 2010. In 2001, he was Chief Executive Officer of [[Lernout & Hauspie|Lernout & Hauspie Speech Product]].\n\nIn addition he was also a member of several other companies, such as: [[Exmar]] where he was President of the Board, he was a board member at [[Ashmore Energy]] (USA), CIB, President of [[Floridienne]], member of the advice committee of ''CSFB Europa'', ''Hermes Asset Management Europe'' Ltd., and of Cobepa/Cobehold. He recently also served as the President of the BeCapital board, a cleantech private equity founded by Cobepa, Compagnie Financi\u00e8re Benjamin de Rothschild and BeCitizen. In the past he was a member of the [[think tank]] [[Coudenberg group]].\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.senate.be/www/?MIval=/showSenator&ID=4125&LANG=fr Philippe Bodson]\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2001_Jan_16/ai_69242511 Statement by Mr. Philippe Bodson on His Nomination as CEO of Lernout and Hauspie]\n* [http://www.freefairpost.com/pdf/CERP%20Forum%2004-Speech%20on%20Access%20to%20Network.pdf Speech for Philippe Bodson] - FFPI Conference\n* [http://becapitalpe.eu/governance/becapital-general-partner Bio of Philippe Bodson as Chairperson of BeCapital, a cleantech private equity fund]\n* [https://www.rtbf.be/info/economie/detail_coronavirus-philippe-bodson-ex-patron-de-tractebel-de-la-feb-et-glaverbel-est-decede-ce-matin?id=10475652]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bodson, Philippe}}\n[[Category:Belgian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Li\u00e8ge alumni]]\n[[Category:INSEAD alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Philippe Andr\u00e9 Eug\u00e8ne, Baron Bodson''' (born 1944 - passed away 4/4/2020) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] businessman.\n\n==Education==\nHe graduated as civil engineer at the [[University of Li\u00e8ge]] (ULg) and obtained a Master of Business Administration at [[INSEAD]] ([[Fontainebleau]], France)\n\n==Career==\nHe started his career at [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] in [[Paris]] where he worked for three years. He then worked for four years for the [[Daus Bank]] in Germany and the United States. In 1977, he started working for [[Glaverbel]], where he would be the [[CEO]] from 1980 until 1989. From September 1989 until December 1998, he was a non-executive member of the board of directors of [[Fortis (finance)|Fortis]]. From 1999 until 2003, he was a [[senator]] in the [[Belgian Senate]] for the [[Mouvement reformateur]]. , From 2004 until 2010, he was a Director at Fortis From 2004 until 2010. In 2001, he was Chief Executive Officer of [[Lernout & Hauspie|Lernout & Hauspie Speech Product]].\n\nIn addition he was also a member of several other companies, such as: [[Exmar]] where he was President of the Board, he was a board member at [[Ashmore Energy]] (USA), CIB, President of [[Floridienne]], member of the advice committee of ''CSFB Europa'', ''Hermes Asset Management Europe'' Ltd., and of Cobepa/Cobehold. He recently also served as the President of the BeCapital board, a cleantech private equity founded by Cobepa, Compagnie Financi\u00e8re Benjamin de Rothschild and BeCitizen. In the past he was a member of the [[think tank]] [[Coudenberg group]].\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.senate.be/www/?MIval=/showSenator&ID=4125&LANG=fr Philippe Bodson]\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2001_Jan_16/ai_69242511 Statement by Mr. Philippe Bodson on His Nomination as CEO of Lernout and Hauspie]\n* [http://www.freefairpost.com/pdf/CERP%20Forum%2004-Speech%20on%20Access%20to%20Network.pdf Speech for Philippe Bodson] - FFPI Conference\n* [http://becapitalpe.eu/governance/becapital-general-partner Bio of Philippe Bodson as Chairperson of BeCapital, a cleantech private equity fund]\n* [https://www.rtbf.be/info/economie/detail_coronavirus-philippe-bodson-ex-patron-de-tractebel-de-la-feb-et-glaverbel-est-decede-ce-matin?id=10475652]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bodson, Philippe}}\n[[Category:Belgian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Li\u00e8ge alumni]]\n[[Category:INSEAD alumni]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AK Kennedy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippe_Bodson"}
{"title_page": "Refilwe Mtsweni-Tsipane", "text_new": "{{short description|5th Premier of Mpumalanga}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Refilwe Mtsweni-Tsipane\n|honorific-suffix = MPL\n|image            =\n|office           = 5th [[Premier of Mpumalanga]]\n|term_start       = 20 March 2018{{efn|Acting:27 February 2018 \u2013 20 March 2018 }}\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[David Mabuza]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Executive Council (South Africa)|Mpumalanga MEC for Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs]]\n|premier1         = [[David Mabuza]]\n|term_start1      = 30 May 2014\n|term_end1        = 27 February 2018\n|predecessor1     = Piet Simon Skhosana\n|successor1       = Speedy Mashilo\n|office2          = Member of the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]]\n|term_start2      = 21 May 2014\n|term_end2        = \n|birthname        = Refilwe Maria Mtsweni\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1973|09|03|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = Lynnville, [[Mpumalanga]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|spouse           = Lawrence Tsipane\n|children         = 2 \n|alma_mater       = [[Tshwane University of Technology]]<br>[[University of the Witwatersrand]]\n|religion         = \n}}\n'''Refilwe Maria Tsipane''' (born 3 September 1973), known as '''Refilwe Mtsweni-Tsipane''' (alternatively spelt '''Mtshweni'''), is a South African politician and member of the [[African National Congress]], who has been serving as the 5th Premier of Mpumalanga since 20 March 2018. She succeeded former Premier [[David Mabuza]] after he was appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]]. Mtsweni-Tsipane is also a Member of the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]] and previously served as the MEC for Co-Operative Governance and Traditional Affairs.<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/mpumalanga-provincial-government/refilwe-mtsweni-ms Refilwe Mtsweni, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\nMtsweni-Tsipane is married to Lawrence Tsipane and has two children.<ref>[https://013.co.za/2019/05/28/refilwe-mtshweni-now-refilwe-tsipane/ Refilwe Mtshweni now goes as Refilwe Tsipane], ''013 News'', 28 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 September 2019.</ref> She spent most of her childhood in [[Emalahleni Local Municipality, Mpumalanga|Lynnville, Emalahleni]], where she went to primary school. She completed her secondary education in [[Atteridgeville]] in [[Pretoria]]. She obtained a Human Resources Diploma from the [[Tshwane University of Technology]] and a Certificate of Leadership and Governance from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>\nYende, Sizwe Sama. [https://city-press.news24.com/News/meet-refilwe-mtshweni-the-mpumalanga-premier-elect-who-quietly-does-her-job-20180318 Meet Refilwe Mtshweni, the Mpumalanga premier-elect who quietly does her job], ''City Press'', 18 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMtsweni-Tsipane was elected to the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]] in 2014 and took office as a Member on 21 May 2014. Premier [[David Mabuza]] announced his new Executive Council in June 2014. Mtsweni-Tsipane was selected as the new MEC for Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs.<ref>[https://ridgetimes.co.za/14088/mabuza-announces-his-new-cabinet/ Mabuza announces new cabinet]. Retrieved on 29 March 2019.</ref> The Democratic Alliance Mpumalanga Provincial Leader, Anthony Benadie, said in a statement that Mtsweni-Tsipane \"lacks the skill or strength of character to manage a complex portfolio\".<ref>[https://ridgetimes.co.za/14082/mabuza-appoints-unknown-and-inexperienced-cabinet/ Mabuza appoints unknown and inexperienced cabinet\u2019 \u2013 DA], Highveld, ''Ridge Times'', 2 June 2014. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, when Mtsweni-Tsipane served as acting Premier of Mpumalanga, she declared a special provincial funeral for the late Ray Phiri.<ref>[https://013.co.za/2017/07/12/acting-premier-refilwe-mtsweni-declares-official-funeral-ray-phiri/ Acting Premier Refilwe Mtsweni declares official funeral for Ray Phiri], ''013News'', 12 July 2017. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018, she was sworn in as acting Premier by Judge President of the Mpumalanga Division of the High Court, Malesela Legodi. The Provincial Democratic Alliance of Mpumalanga said that the swearing-in of Mtsweni-Tsipane was \"unconstitutional\" because former Premier David Mabuza was not in the liberty to appoint an acting Premier to a position that he no longer holds.<ref>de Villiers, Mireille. [https://citizen.co.za/news/news-cns/1840599/mpumalanga-admits-swearing-in-of-acting-premier-was-unconstitutional/ Mpumalanga admits swearing in of acting premier was unconstitutional], ''TheCitizen'', 1 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nShe was sworn in for a second time as acting Premier on 1 March 2018 in Pretoria.<ref>[http://www.ziwaphi.com/2018/03/06/speakers-blunder-mars-appointment-of-first-female-premier/ Speaker\u2019s blunder mars appointment of first female premier], ''Ziwaphi'', 6 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref> On 14 March 2018, the ANC officially nominated Mtsweni-Tsipane to become the Premier of Mpumalanga. She served as Premier-elect until the legislature confirmed her to the position on 20 March 2018.<ref>Mahlase, Mahlatse. [https://mg.co.za/article/2018-03-14-anc-elects-female-premiers-for-mpumalanga-and-free-state ANC elects female premiers for Mpumalanga and Free State], ''Mail & Guardian'', 14 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>  She was formally inaugurated on 20 March 2018 by Judge President Malesela Legodi. She is the first woman to hold the role.<ref>[https://mpumalanganews.co.za/333972/breaking-news-new-premier-realigns-cabinet/ BREAKING NEWS: New premier realigns cabinet], ''Mpumalanga News'', 20 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, the [[African National Congress]] announced that it had retained Mtsweni-Tsipane as Premier of Mpumalanga. She took office for her first full term on 27 May 2019.<ref>Madia, Tshidi, Tandwa, Lizeka. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/these-are-the-ancs-premier-candidates-but-no-name-yet-for-troubled-north-west-20190513 These are the ANC's premier candidates, but no name yet for troubled North West], ''Elections '19'', 13 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 May 2019.</ref><ref>Hlatshwayo, Yoliswa, Khumalo, Jabulane. [https://mpumalanganews.co.za/357686/premier-refilwe-tsipane-commits-protect-constitution/ Premier Refilwe Tsipane commits to protect constitution], ''Mpumalanga News'', 27 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 September 2019.</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/refilwe-maria-mtshweni/ People's Assembly profile]\n{{MpumaPremiers}}\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Mabuza]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=5th [[Premier of Mpumalanga]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mtsweni-Tspane, Refilwe}}\n[[Category:Premiers of Mpumalanga]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tshwane University of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|5th Premier of Mpumalanga}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Refilwe Mtsweni-Tsipane\n|honorific-suffix = MPL\n|image            =\n|office           = 5th [[Premier of Mpumalanga]]\n|term_start       = 20 March 2018<br /> <small>Acting: 27 February 2018 \u2013 20 March 2018</small>\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[David Mabuza]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Executive Council (South Africa)|Mpumalanga MEC for Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs]]\n|premier1         = [[David Mabuza]]\n|term_start1      = 30 May 2014\n|term_end1        = 27 February 2018\n|predecessor1     = Piet Simon Skhosana\n|successor1       = Speedy Mashilo\n|office2          = Member of the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]]\n|term_start2      = 21 May 2014\n|term_end2        = \n|birthname        = Refilwe Maria Mtsweni\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1973|09|03|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = Lynnville, [[Mpumalanga]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|spouse           = Lawrence Tsipane\n|children         = 2 \n|alma_mater       = [[Tshwane University of Technology]]<br>[[University of the Witwatersrand]]\n|religion         = \n}}\n'''Refilwe Maria Tsipane''' (born 3 September 1973), known as '''Refilwe Mtsweni-Tsipane''' (alternatively spelt '''Mtshweni'''), is a South African politician and member of the [[African National Congress]], who has been serving as the 5th Premier of Mpumalanga since 20 March 2018. She succeeded former Premier [[David Mabuza]] after he was appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]]. Mtsweni-Tsipane is also a Member of the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]] and previously served as the MEC for Co-Operative Governance and Traditional Affairs.<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/mpumalanga-provincial-government/refilwe-mtsweni-ms Refilwe Mtsweni, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\nMtsweni-Tsipane is married to Lawrence Tsipane and has two children.<ref>[https://013.co.za/2019/05/28/refilwe-mtshweni-now-refilwe-tsipane/ Refilwe Mtshweni now goes as Refilwe Tsipane], ''013 News'', 28 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 September 2019.</ref> She spent most of her childhood in [[Emalahleni Local Municipality, Mpumalanga|Lynnville, Emalahleni]], where she went to primary school. She completed her secondary education in [[Atteridgeville]] in [[Pretoria]]. She obtained a Human Resources Diploma from the [[Tshwane University of Technology]] and a Certificate of Leadership and Governance from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>\nYende, Sizwe Sama. [https://city-press.news24.com/News/meet-refilwe-mtshweni-the-mpumalanga-premier-elect-who-quietly-does-her-job-20180318 Meet Refilwe Mtshweni, the Mpumalanga premier-elect who quietly does her job], ''City Press'', 18 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMtsweni-Tsipane was elected to the [[Mpumalanga Provincial Legislature]] in 2014 and took office as a Member on 21 May 2014. Premier [[David Mabuza]] announced his new Executive Council in June 2014. Mtsweni-Tsipane was selected as the new MEC for Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs.<ref>[https://ridgetimes.co.za/14088/mabuza-announces-his-new-cabinet/ Mabuza announces new cabinet]. Retrieved on 29 March 2019.</ref> The Democratic Alliance Mpumalanga Provincial Leader, Anthony Benadie, said in a statement that Mtsweni-Tsipane \"lacks the skill or strength of character to manage a complex portfolio\".<ref>[https://ridgetimes.co.za/14082/mabuza-appoints-unknown-and-inexperienced-cabinet/ Mabuza appoints unknown and inexperienced cabinet\u2019 \u2013 DA], Highveld, ''Ridge Times'', 2 June 2014. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, when Mtsweni-Tsipane served as acting Premier of Mpumalanga, she declared a special provincial funeral for the late Ray Phiri.<ref>[https://013.co.za/2017/07/12/acting-premier-refilwe-mtsweni-declares-official-funeral-ray-phiri/ Acting Premier Refilwe Mtsweni declares official funeral for Ray Phiri], ''013News'', 12 July 2017. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018, she was sworn in as acting Premier by Judge President of the Mpumalanga Division of the High Court, Malesela Legodi. The Provincial Democratic Alliance of Mpumalanga said that the swearing-in of Mtsweni-Tsipane was \"unconstitutional\" because former Premier David Mabuza was not in the liberty to appoint an acting Premier to a position that he no longer holds.<ref>de Villiers, Mireille. [https://citizen.co.za/news/news-cns/1840599/mpumalanga-admits-swearing-in-of-acting-premier-was-unconstitutional/ Mpumalanga admits swearing in of acting premier was unconstitutional], ''TheCitizen'', 1 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nShe was sworn in for a second time as acting Premier on 1 March 2018 in Pretoria.<ref>[http://www.ziwaphi.com/2018/03/06/speakers-blunder-mars-appointment-of-first-female-premier/ Speaker\u2019s blunder mars appointment of first female premier], ''Ziwaphi'', 6 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref> On 14 March 2018, the ANC officially nominated Mtsweni-Tsipane to become the Premier of Mpumalanga. She served as Premier-elect until the legislature confirmed her to the position on 20 March 2018.<ref>Mahlase, Mahlatse. [https://mg.co.za/article/2018-03-14-anc-elects-female-premiers-for-mpumalanga-and-free-state ANC elects female premiers for Mpumalanga and Free State], ''Mail & Guardian'', 14 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>  She was formally inaugurated on 20 March 2018 by Judge President Malesela Legodi. She is the first woman to hold the role.<ref>[https://mpumalanganews.co.za/333972/breaking-news-new-premier-realigns-cabinet/ BREAKING NEWS: New premier realigns cabinet], ''Mpumalanga News'', 20 March 2018. Retrieved on 11 January 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, the [[African National Congress]] announced that it had retained Mtsweni-Tsipane as Premier of Mpumalanga. She took office for her first full term on 27 May 2019.<ref>Madia, Tshidi, Tandwa, Lizeka. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/these-are-the-ancs-premier-candidates-but-no-name-yet-for-troubled-north-west-20190513 These are the ANC's premier candidates, but no name yet for troubled North West], ''Elections '19'', 13 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 May 2019.</ref><ref>Hlatshwayo, Yoliswa, Khumalo, Jabulane. [https://mpumalanganews.co.za/357686/premier-refilwe-tsipane-commits-protect-constitution/ Premier Refilwe Tsipane commits to protect constitution], ''Mpumalanga News'', 27 May 2019. Retrieved on 13 September 2019.</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/refilwe-maria-mtshweni/ People's Assembly profile]\n{{MpumaPremiers}}\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Mabuza]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=5th [[Premier of Mpumalanga]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mtsweni-Tspane, Refilwe}}\n[[Category:Premiers of Mpumalanga]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tshwane University of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adjustments", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Refilwe_Mtsweni-Tsipane"}
{"title_page": "A Flock of Seagulls", "text_new": "{{redirect|AFOS|ankle-foot orthotics|Orthotics|AFOs as a plural|AFO (disambiguation)}}\n{{about|the British new wave band|the band's self-titled debut album|A Flock of Seagulls (album)}}\n{{short description|English new wave and synth-pop band}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = A Flock of Seagulls\n| image            = Mike Score.jpg\n| caption          = Lead singer [[Mike Score]] performing in 2011\n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Liverpool]], England\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[New wave music|New wave]]<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web|first= Stephen Thomas |last= Erlewine |title= A Flock of Seagulls \u2013 Artist Biography |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/a-flock-of-seagulls-mn0000567862/biography |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= 27 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|first= Colin |last= Larkin |authorlink= Colin Larkin (writer) |title= [[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]] |year= 2011 |chapter= A Flock of Seagulls |edition= 5th |publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA1909&dq=%22new+wave+electro+pop%22 |isbn= 0-85-712595-8}}</ref>|[[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=\"Larkin\"/>}}\n| years_active     = {{hlist|1979\u20131986|1988\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Jive Records|Jive]]|[[I.R.S. Records|I.R.S.]]|Cocteau}}\n| website          = {{URL|www.aflockofseagulls.org}}\n| current_members  = [[Mike Score]]<br/>Pando<br/>Kevin Rankin<br/>Gord Deppe\n| past_members     = [[#Members|List of former members]]\n}}\n'''A Flock of Seagulls''' are an English [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[synth-pop]] band originally formed in 1979 in [[Liverpool]] by [[Mike Score|Michael \"Mike\" Score]] (lead vocals, keyboards), his brother Alister \"Ali\" James Score (drums), and Francis Lee \"Frank\" Maudsley (bass), with their most famous line-up consisting of the Score brothers, Maudsley, and lead guitarist [[Paul Reynolds (musician)|Paul Reynolds]].\n\nThe group had a string of international hit singles including \"[[I Ran (So Far Away)]]\" (1982), \"[[Space Age Love Song]]\" (1982), \"[[Wishing (If I Had a Photograph of You)]]\" (1982), and \"[[The More You Live, the More You Love]]\" (1984). They first became notable in the 1980s for their music video for \"I Ran (So Far Away)\" that received airplay on [[MTV]] during the [[Second British Invasion]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Parke |last= Puterbaugh |title= Anglomania: The Second British Invasion |magazine= Rolling Stone |date= 10 November 1983 |accessdate= 11 May 2019 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/anglomania-the-second-british-invasion-52016/}}</ref> The band won a [[Grammy Award]] in 1983 for their instrumental \"[[D.N.A. (A Flock of Seagulls song)|D.N.A]]\" (1982).\n\n==History==\n\n===1979\u20131986: Formative years and mainstream success===\nA Flock of Seagulls was started by [[Mike Score]] in late 1979 in Liverpool.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= A Flock of Seagulls: A Flock of Seagulls |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume= 94 |issue= 22 |page= 30 |date= 5 June 1982 |accessdate= 5 January 2020 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=UyQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT29}}</ref> The band's name was taken from the song \"Toiler on the Sea\" by [[Punk rock|punk]] band [[the Stranglers]]  and the book ''[[Jonathan Livingston Seagull]]'', according to Mike Score.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Walter |last= Bird Jr. |title= Mike Score still flying with Flock of Seagulls |magazine= [[Worcester Magazine]] |date= 26 April 2017 |accessdate= 6 June 2018 |url= https://worcestermag.com/2017/04/26/mike-score-still-flying-with-flock-of-seagulls}}</ref> The inaugural line-up of the band featured Mike, who was previously a hairdresser, on lead vocals and keyboards, Ali Score on drums, and Frank Maudsley on bass. The band added Willie Woo on guitar; and then brought in Mark Edmondson to replace Ali on drums when the Score brothers had a falling-out.<ref>{{cite web|title= A Flock of Seagulls \u2013 Biography |publisher= [[Amoeba Music]] |url= http://www.amoeba.com/a-flock-of-seagulls/artist/136931/bio |accessdate= 15 June 2016}}</ref> Not long afterwards, Edmondson departed to make way for a returning Ali; and shortly thereafter Woo departed the band and was replaced by teenager [[Paul Reynolds (musician)|Paul Reynolds]], who had been a close friend of Edmondson, at the behest of Maudsley; thus creating the band's classic line-up. After practising above Score's hair salon,<ref name=\"DT\">{{cite book|first= Dave |last= Thompson |authorlink= Dave Thompson (author) |title= Alternative Rock |year= 2000 |publisher= [[Hal Leonard Corporation]] |pages= 141\u201342 |isbn= 978-0-8793-0607-6 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHP-r9-eqdAC&pg=PA141}}</ref> the band started playing clubs and eventually got a recording contract.\n\nThey recorded radio sessions for [[John Peel]]'s [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] on 6 May 1981, which aired six days later.<ref>{{cite web|title= BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Keeping It Peel \u2013 06/05/1980 A Flock of Seagulls |publisher= [[BBC Radio 1]] |accessdate= 12 June 2018 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/sessions/1980s/1981/May06aflockofseagulls/}}</ref> Eventually, under the management of Harry Maguire, Tommy Crossan, and Mick Rossi, all directors of Checkmount Limited, they began to release singles through [[Jive Records]]. The group released their debut single \"[[Talking (A Flock of Seagulls song)|Talking]]\" (produced by Nelson), on [[Bill Nelson (musician)|Bill Nelson]]'s Cocteau label. They were then signed to major label Jive, distributed through CBS records, where they released their second single \"[[Telecommunication (song)|Telecommunication]]\". The single was also produced by Nelson and became a club hit. Their third release was the EP \"Modern Love is Automatic\". Originally released as a 4 track EP on both 7\" and 12\", the 12\" edition was soon reissued, adding \"Telecommunication\". This 5 track EP was also their first release in the U.S.<ref name=\"DT\"/> In 1982, the group's fourth single \"[[I Ran (So Far Away)]]\", produced by [[Mike Howlett]], the former bass player of the band [[Gong (band)|Gong]], became a worldwide hit, reaching number 1 in Australia and the Top 10 in both the US and New Zealand. Their [[A Flock of Seagulls (album)|debut album]] and single \"[[Space Age Love Song]]\" were both successful.<ref>{{cite journal|first= Andy |last= Greene |title= Where Are They Now? 1982's Biggest Pop Acts \u2013 A Flock of Seagulls |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/where-are-they-now-1982s-biggest-pop-acts-20120808/a-flock-of-seagulls-0758690 |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= 8 August 2012 |accessdate= 22 March 2015}}</ref> The track \"[[D.N.A. (A Flock of Seagulls song)|D.N.A.]]\" won a [[Grammy Award]] in [[25th Annual Grammy Awards|1983]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Instrumental Performance|Best Rock Instrumental Performance]].<ref>{{cite web|title= A Flock of Seagulls \u2013 Awards |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/a-flock-of-seagulls-mn0000567862/awards |website= AllMusic |accessdate= 6 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Artist: Flock of Seagulls |website= Grammy.com |accessdate= 27 April 2019 |url= https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/flock-seagulls}}</ref> In late 1982, the band finally found major success in their home country with \"[[Wishing (If I Had a Photograph of You)]]\", the first single from their next album ''[[Listen (A Flock of Seagulls album)|Listen]]'', which reached the Top 10.<ref>{{cite web|title= A Flock of Seagulls |publisher= [[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate= 6 November 2013 |url= http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/19502/A%20FLOCK%20OF%20SEAGULLS/}}</ref> Later, the band was praised for having broken the ground for other musical acts during the advent of the video music area,<ref>{{cite web|first= Charles R. |last= Cross |authorlink= Charles R. Cross |title= Never mind the hair bands, here's a Flock of Seagulls! |url= http://www.salon.com/2001/08/30/eighties/ |work= [[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date= 30 August 2001 |accessdate= 6 November 2013}}</ref> but as it turned out, 1982 was the peak year of their commercial and critical success.\n\nOn Memorial Day Weekend, Saturday, 28 May 1983, A Flock of Seagulls performed at the [[US Festival]] along with [[Oingo Boingo]], [[Men at Work]], and others.<ref>{{cite news|first= Ben |last= Wener |title= The Forgotten Festival: Remembering US '82 and '83 as Steve Wozniak's dream bash turns 30 |newspaper= [[Orange County Register]] |date= 31 August 2012 |accessdate= 7 June 2018 |url= https://www.ocregister.com/2012/08/31/the-forgotten-festival-remembering-us-82-and-83-as-steve-wozniaks-dream-bash-turns-30/}}</ref> Three more singles were released from ''Listen'' in 1983, including a re-recorded version of their debut single \"(It's Not Me) Talking\", but they were only minor successes in the UK and abroad. Faced with disappointment, the group changed direction from their [[science fiction]] themes and produced a more conceptual emotion-based third album in 1984 called ''[[The Story of a Young Heart]]'', with \"[[The More You Live, the More You Love]]\" as the lead single. Despite heavy rotation on [[MTV]] and other music video shows at that time, the single was only moderately successful, and the album's other two singles \u2013 \"Never Again (The Dancer)\" and \"Remember David\" (released only in a few European countries) \u2013 did not make any headway. Faced with sliding sales and a loss of direction, the band continued to consider their options whilst touring. During this period, Paul Reynolds left the band, and was replaced by Gary Steadman (from [[Classix Nouveaux]]).<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Keyboardist Chris Chryssaphis was added at the same time to augment their sound.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Both stayed in the band for the recording and release of next the album\u2013''[[Dream Come True (A Flock of Seagulls album)|Dream Come True\u2013]]''but departed once the tour had ended. The album was released in 1985 in the UK and 1986 in the US, and failed to chart, thus leading to the dissolving of the band until 1988.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n===1988\u2013present: Reformation and the current era===\nThe band's lineup had a complete modification in 1988 in [[Philadelphia]] with a lineup composed of Mike Score along with numerous local musicians, consisting of guitarists Ed Berner and Dave Maerz, bass guitarist Mike Radcliffe, keyboardist Mike Railton, and drummers Kaya Pryor and Jonte Wilkins.<ref>{{cite news|first= Jonathan |last= Takiff |title= Local Seagulls Join The Flock |date= 18 November 1988 |newspaper= [[Philadelphia Daily News]] |url= http://articles.philly.com/1988-11-18/news/26246682_1_seagulls-ed-berner-culture-club |accessdate= 15 June 2016}}</ref> This lineup expanded the following year to include drummer [[Michael Marquart|Mike Marquart]];<ref>{{cite web|first= Martin C. |last= Strong |authorlink= Martin C. Strong |title= A Flock of Seagulls |url= http://thegreatrockbible.com/portfolio-item/flock-seagulls-biography/ |accessdate= 15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Malcolm |last= Venable |title= Low-key musician doesn\u2019t need to be a big rock star |date= 13 October 2009 |newspaper= [[The Virginian-Pilot]] |url= http://hamptonroads.com/2009/10/lowkey-musician-doesn%E2%80%99t-need-be-big-rock-star |accessdate= 15 June 2016}}</ref> but was then reduced to a five-piece band consisting of Score, Berner, Pryor, Radcliffe, and Railton; it was this lineup which released the single \"Magic\" that same year.\n\nIn 1994, the band's lineup changed again; this time to a formation consisting of Score, Berner, and new recruits A.J. Mazzetti (drums) and Dean Pichette (bass guitar). This lineup recorded the album ''[[The Light at the End of the World (A Flock of Seagulls album)|The Light at the End of the World]]'' in 1996, but it failed to chart.\n\nIn 1998, Berner, Mazzetti, and Pichette departed the band and were replaced by Joe Rodriguez, Darryl Sons, and Rob Wright, respectively. In 1999, the band re-recorded the [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] song \"[[This Used to Be My Playground]]\" for the 2000 Madonna tribute album ''The World's Greatest 80s Tribute to Madonna''. In November 2003, the original lineup of Mike and Ali Score, Paul Reynolds and Frank Maudsley reunited for a one-off performance on the VH1 series ''[[Bands Reunited]]''. In September 2004, they reformed again and did a brief tour in the United States. Though the tour continued to be advertised as the \"original lineup\", later shows no longer included the original band, but was Mike Score's continuation of the newer band; which by this point consisted of Score, Rodriguez, and new recruits Michael Brahm (drums), and Pando (bass guitar). In 2005, this version of the group starred in the American version of the entertainment show ''[[Hit Me, Baby, One More Time (TV series)|Hit Me Baby, One More Time]]'', where they performed \"I Ran\" and a cover of [[Ryan Cabrera]]'s song, \"[[On the Way Down|On The Way Down]]\" for a chance to have $20,000 donated to a charity of their choice.\n\nIn June 2011, Frank Maudsley and Paul Reynolds performed at [[Croxteth Hall|Croxteth Park]] music festival in Liverpool, under the name 'A Flock of Seagulls'.<ref>{{cite web|title= 80's Band A Flock of Seagulls top Croxteth Free Music Festival lineup |website= LLTV |date= 25 June 2011 |accessdate= 22 August 2019 |url= http://liverpool-live.tv/uncategorized/80s-band-a-flock-of-seagulls-top-croxteth-free-music-festival-lineup/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Jade |last= Wright |title= Jade Wright recommends . . .Croxteth Park Free Music Festival |newspaper= [[Liverpool Echo]] |date= 10 June 2011 |accessdate= 22 August 2019 |url= https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/music/jade-wright-recommends---3372111}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2013, Mike Score indicated via his YouTube account that he was pursuing his solo career. He released the singles \"All I Wanna Do\" in February 2013,<ref>{{cite web|first= Paul |last= Waller |title= Flock-of-Seagulls/Mike-Score |work= Penny Black Music |date= 24 January 2013 |accessdate= 7 June 2018 |url= http://www.pennyblackmusic.co.uk/magsitepages/Article/6825/Flock-of-Seagulls/Mike-Score/}}</ref> and \"Somebody Like You\" in January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title= A Flock of Seagulls' Mike Score Releases New Single 'Somebody Like You' |website= [[Broadway Worldwide]] |date= 29 January 2014 |accessdate= 12 June 2018 |url= http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/A-Flock-of-Seagulls-Mike-Score-Releases-New-Single-Somebody-Like-You-20140129}}</ref> In late July 2013, after a Southern California performance, Mike Score told the Los Angeles Daily News that the band's rented van that contained $70,000 of equipment and the hard drives that stored tracks for his solo album ''[[Zeebratta]]'' were stolen from a Comfort Inn.<ref>{{cite web|last= Associated Press |title= Flock of Seagulls Tour Van Stolen With Instruments, New Album Inside |work= Billboard |date= 23 July 2013 |accessdate= 7 June 2018 |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/4312296/flock-of-seagulls-tour-van-stolen-with-instruments-new-album-inside/}}</ref> While this delayed the album's release, he was able to reconstruct it with music files from his home in Florida. ''Zeebratta'' was finally released on 1 March 2014.\n\nKevin Rankin replaced Brahm on drums in 2016, and Gordon Deppe\u2014from the Canadian band [[Spoons (band)|Spoons]]\u2014replaced Joe Rodriguez in December 2017.\n\nOn 3 May 2018, it was announced that the band's original four members were reuniting to record a new album titled ''[[Ascension (A Flock of Seagulls album)|Ascension]]'', their first studio recording since 1984.<ref>{{cite web|first= Mackenzie |last= Cummings-Grady |title= A Flock of Seagulls Announces New Album 'Ascension' |work= Billboard |date= 3 May 2018 |accessdate= 27 May 2018 |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8453567/a-flock-of-seagulls-announces-new-album-reunion}}</ref> Featuring the [[Prague Philharmonic Orchestra]], it would be a 10-track album composed of new renditions of their previous hits alongside one new song.<ref>{{cite web|title= Fully Reunited, A Flock of Seagulls Readying New LP 'Ascension,' with the Prague Philharmonic Orchestra |work= Rock Cellar Magazine |date= 7 May 2018 |accessdate= 2 June 2018 |url= https://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2018/05/07/flock-of-seagulls-reunion-new-album/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141111/https://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2018/05/07/flock-of-seagulls-reunion-new-album/ |archivedate= 12 June 2018 |url-status= dead}}</ref> The video for \"Space Age Love Song\" premiered on YouTube on 6 June,<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Magnet Exclusive: Premiere of A Flock of Seagulls' \"Space Age Love Song\" Video |magazine= [[Magnet (magazine)|Magnet]] |date= 6 June 2018 |accessdate= 7 June 2018 |url= http://magnetmagazine.com/2018/06/06/magnet-exclusive-premiere-flock-seagulls-space-age-love-song-video/}}</ref> and an EP featuring five versions of the song was released digitally two days later.<ref>{{cite web|first= Julia |last= Gray |title= A Flock of Seagulls' Original Lineup Remade Their Best Song for First Recording in 34 Years |website= [[Stereogum]] |date= 7 June 2018 |accessdate= 8 June 2018 |url= https://www.stereogum.com/2000470/a-flock-of-seagulls-original-lineup-remade-their-best-song-for-first-recording-in-34-years/video/}}</ref> The album was available in physical form in late June 2018, then released digitally and in stores on 6 July.<ref>{{cite web|title= A Flock of Seagulls \u2013 Ascension |website= AllMusic |accessdate= 8 July 2018 |url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/ascension-mw0003184896}}</ref> In December 2018, the orchestral version of \"I Ran\" was released as a single.\n\n==Legacy==\nDue to their memorable and unusual style and appearance, A Flock of Seagulls are sometimes referred to with ironic appreciation. The ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' wrote: \"Of course, everyone remembers this group now for singer Mike Score's ridiculous back-combed haircut and the fact that they are mentioned in ''[[Pulp Fiction]]''. So now they're kind of cool, but in the early 1980s it was a different story.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title= 252\u2013281: The '80s |journal= 501 Lost Songs |page= 53 |publisher= [[NME]] |year= 2011}}</ref> Additionally, the band was featured on Viacom's [[VH1]] and Sony's BMG Legacy Recordings' 2006 revival CD series and multi-platform marketing campaign, \"[[We Are the 80's]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Michael |last= Paoletta |title= Making The Brand: An '80s Revival |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 22 July 2006 |volume= 118 |issue= 29 |page= 13 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KxYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13}}</ref> In a 2007 article for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Alfred Hickling described the group as \"dreadful\", and unfavourably compared them to Liverpool new wave peers [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark|OMD]] and other acts of the time.<ref name=\"EH\">{{cite news|first= Alfred |last= Hickling |title= The Electric Hills |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |url= https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2007/mar/19/theatre1 |date= 19 March 2007 |accessdate= 5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nTheir dramatic style has drawn much criticism and parody, but the band has also been recognized as a pioneering act, capturing the spirit of their time, particularly with the guitar work of Paul Reynolds and sonically multi-layered hits such as \"Space Age Love Song,\" \"Telecommunication,\" and \"Modern Love Is Automatic.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Megan M. |last= Carpenter |title= Space Age Love Song: The Mix Tape in a Digital Universe |url= http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&context=megan_carpenter |publisher= Works.bepress.com |year= 2010 |accessdate= 6 November 2013 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140201133053/http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&context=megan_carpenter |archivedate= 1 February 2014 |url-status= dead}}</ref> The band also is noted for creating a successful [[concept album]], their debut, which alludes to an alien invasion of earth.<ref>{{cite book|first= Janell R. |last= Duxbury |title= Shakespeare Meets the Backbeat: Literary Allusion in Rock Music |year= 1988 |publisher= [[Taylor & Francis]]}}</ref> Billboard writer [[Robert Christgau]] applauded their \"mechanical lyrics, about a mechanical end of the world,\" while noting the \"aural pleasure\" of both the band's debut album and the follow-up.<ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |authorlink= Robert Christgau |title= A Flock of Seagulls |series= Christgau's Consumer Guide |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |date= 30 November 1982 |accessdate= 6 August 2014 |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv7-83.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |title= A Flock of Seagulls: Listen |series= Christgau's Consumer Guide |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv11b-82.php |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |date= 26 July 1983 |accessdate= 6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video for \"I Ran\" was low budget (even for the time) but enjoyed enormous success, and is well-remembered in part due to its heavy rotation on MTV.<ref>{{cite book|first= MaryAnn |last= Janosik |title= The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Rock History: The video generation, 1981\u20131990 |year= 2006 |publisher= [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood Press]] |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eSIKAQAAMAAJ |isbn= 978-0-3133-2943-2}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Members===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Current members\n* [[Mike Score]] \u2013 lead vocals, keyboards, guitar <small>(1979\u20131986, 1988\u2013present)</small>\n* Pando \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n* Kevin Rankin \u2013 drums <small>(2016\u2013present)</small>\n* Gord Deppe \u2013 lead guitar <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-2}}\n;Former members\n* Frank Maudsley \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1979\u20131986, 2003, 2004, 2018)</small>\n* Ali Score \u2013 drums <small>(1979, 1979\u201386, 2003, 2004, 2018)</small>\n* Willie Woo \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1980)</small>\n* Mark Edmondson \u2013 drums <small>(1980)</small>\n* [[Paul Reynolds (musician)|Paul Reynolds]] \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1980\u20131984, 2003, 2004, 2018)</small>\n* Chris Chryssaphis \u2013 keyboards <small>(1984\u20131985)</small>\n* Gary Steadman \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1984\u20131985)</small>\n* Ed Berner \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1988\u20131998)</small>\n* Dave Maerz \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1988\u20131989)</small>\n* Kaya Pryor \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1988\u20131994)</small>\n* Mike Radcliffe \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1988\u20131994)</small>\n* Mike Railton \u2013 keyboards <small>(1988\u20131994)</small>\n* Jonte Wilkins \u2013 drums <small>(1988\u20131989)</small>\n* [[Michael Marquart|Mike Marquart]] \u2013 drums <small>(1989)</small>\n* Shavin Duffy \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1990)</small>\n* A.J. Mazzetti \u2013 drums <small>(1994\u20131998)</small>\n* Dean Pichette \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1994\u20131998)</small>\n* Joe Rodriguez \u2013 lead guitar <small>(1998\u20132017)</small>\n* Lucio Rubino  \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1998\u20132002)</small>\n* John Walker \u2013 drums <small>(1995\u20131998)</small>\n* Darryl Sons \u2013 drums <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n* Rob Wright \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n* Robbie Hanson \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1999\u20132006)</small>\n* Albert Cruz \u2013 drums <small>(2001\u20132006)</small>\n* Michael Brahm \u2013 drums <small>(2004\u20132016)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:18\nPlotArea = left:120 bottom:60 top:0 right:10\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1979 till:01/01/2020\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n  id:vocals value:red legend:Vocals\n  id:guitars value:green legend:guitar\n  id:bass value:blue legend:Bass\n  id:drums value:orange legend:Drums,_percussion\n  id:keys value:purple legend:Keyboards\n  id:lines value:black legend:Studio_albums\n\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:3 start:1979\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1979\n\nBarData =\n   bar:Mike text:Mike Score\n   bar:Willie text:Willie Woo\n   bar:Paul text:Paul Reynolds\n   bar:Gary text:Gary Steadman\n   bar:Ed text:Ed Berner \n   bar:Dave text:Dave Maerz\n   bar:Joe text:Joe Rodriguez\n   bar:Gord text:Gord Deppe\n   bar:Frank text:Frank Maudsley\n   bar:Radcliffe text:Mike Radcliffe\n   bar:Duffy text:Shavin Duffy\n   bar:Dean text:Dean Pichette\n   bar:Lucio text:Lucio Rubino\n   bar:Rob text:Rob Wright\n   bar:Robbie text: Robbie Hanson\n   bar:Pando text:Pando\n   bar:Chris text:Chris Chryssaphis\n   bar:Railton text:Mike Railton\n   bar:Ali text:Ali Score\n   bar:Mark text:Mark Edmondson\n   bar:Jonte text:Jonte Wilkins\n   bar:Marquart text:Mike Marquart\n   bar:Kaya text:Kaya Pryor \n   bar:Jonte text:Jonte Wilkins\n   bar:A.J.      text:A.J. Mazzetti\n   bar:John text:John Walker\n   bar:Darryl text:Darryl Sons\n   bar:Albert text:Albert Cruz\n   bar:Michael text:Michael Brahm\n   bar:Kevin text:Kevin Rankin\n\nLineData =\n   at:04/30/1982 color:black layer:back\n   at:05/15/1983 color:black layer:back\n   at:07/09/1984 color:black layer:back\n   at:11/01/1985 color:black layer:back\n   at:03/14/1995 color:black layer:back\n   at:06/07/2018 color:black layer:back\n\nPlotData =\n width:11 textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(-11,-4)\n  bar:Mike from:01/01/1979 ti