ring his congressional stint, he was among the 'Spice Boys' who were instrumental in the [[Second EDSA Revolution|ousting]] of former [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|Philippine President]] [[Joseph Estrada]]. He was also a law professor in four universities, namely [[Miriam College|Maryknoll College]], [[San Beda College]], [[Far Eastern University]], and [[Manila Central University]].\n\nEchiverri was elected mayor in 2004 defeating Gigi Malonzo, Egay Erice, Macario \"Boy\" Asistio, Jr., and Luis \"Baby\" Asistio. He had been mayor for three terms from 2004-2013. During the 2013 elections, his son Ricojudge ran for mayoralty but lost to then representative for the city's north district [[Oscar Malapitan]].\n\nEchiverri ran for Mayor in the  [[2016 Philippine general election|2016]], but lost to incumbent mayor Oscar Malapitan.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/784987/incumbent-caloocan-mayor-beats-iglesia-backed-foe | title=Malapitan wins reelection | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer]] | date=May 11, 2016 | accessdate=October 24, 2019 | first=Jodee A. |last=Agoncillo}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Dangal ng Bayan Award for Public Service, 12th Annual Asia-Pacific Excellence Award \n* Huwarang Ama for Public Service / Outstanding Father of the Year, National Mother's Day & Father's Day Awards \n* Innovative Solutions to Dumps and Waste Award (\u201cOut of the Box Award\u201d), Mother Earth Foundation\n* Bagong Bayani ng Caloocan Award, Humanitarian Mission \n* Recognition Award for the successful & effective implementation of DILG-NCR Programs, [[Department of the Interior and Local Government]] \n* Plaque of Merit, 2nd Best City Police Station of the Year, Philippine National Police \n* Distinguished Public Service Award - Exemplary Performance as a Leader, [[Integrated Bar of the Philippines]] \n* Hall of Fame Awardee, Most Outstanding Congressman, Congress Magazine, Makati Graduate School & Metropolitan Disseminators of Information Association (MEDIA) \n* [[Ramon Mitra, Jr.|Hon. Ramon V. Mitra]] [[San Beda College|Bedan]] Award for Legislation \n* \"Huwarang Filipino Awardee for Government & Public Service,\" Gintong Anak/Ina Awards, Parangal ng Bayan Foundation \n* \"Outstanding Legislator of the Year, Public Servant of the New Millennium,\u201d  Phil. Media Research and Progress Report Inc. \n* 2003 Year-Ender Excellence Award, National Consumers Affairs Foundation \n* [[Paul P. Harris|Paul Harris Fellow]], [[Rotary International]] \n* Most Outstanding City Councilor, [[League of Barangays of the Philippines|Association of Barangay Council]], 1992 \n* Most Outstanding Alumnus, [[De La Salle Araneta University|Araneta University Foundation High School]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Mayor.Echiverri/] http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=echiverri-e&pg=coauth\n*[http://www.philstar.com/metro/574418/incumbents-still-win-caloocan] [http://ncr.dilg.gov.ph/home/index.php/news/177-dilg-recognizes-exemplary-local-government-units-of-the-national-capital-region http://ncr.dilg.gov.ph/home/index.php/news/177-dilg-recognizes-exemplary-local-government-units-of-the-national-capital-regio][http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/08/27/08/marjorie-barretto-%E2%80%98-time-finally-speak-up%E2%80%99][http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=echiverri-e&pg=auth]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Echiverri, Enrico}}\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Caloocan]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Metro Manila city and municipal councilors]]\n[[Category:People from Caloocan]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:San Beda University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "112.201.48.146", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enrico_Echiverri"}
{"title_page": "Thomas McMillan (footballer)", "text_new": "{{other people||Thomas McMillan (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas McMillan}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|        name = Thomas McMillan\n|       image = \n|    fullname = Thomas McMillan\n|  birth_date = 11 October 1866\n| birth_place = [[Mauchline]], Scotland\n|  death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1928|01|02|1866|10|11}}\n|      height = \n|    position = \n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 = [[Mauchline F.C.|Mauchline]]\n| years1 =  1884\u20131885\n| years2 =  1885\u20131895\n| clubs1 =  Dumbarton Athletic\n| clubs2 =  [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]<ref>{{cite book | last = McAllister | first = Jim | title = The Sons of the Rock \u2013 The Official History of Dumbarton Football Club | publisher = J&J Robertson Printers | year = 2002 | location = Dumbarton}}</ref>\n| caps1 =             \n| caps2 =             \n| caps3 =  71 \n| goals1 =   \n| goals2 =   \n| goals3 =  4\n| nationalyears1= 1887\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1= 0\n| nationalyears2= 1894\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2= 0}}\n\n'''Thomas McMillan''' (11 October 1866 \u2013 2 January 1928) was a Scottish [[association football|footballer]].\n\n==Career==\nMcMillan played for [[Mauchline F.C.|Mauchline]], Dumbarton Athletic, [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Emms | first1 = Steve | last2 = Wells |first2 = Richard | title = Scottish League Players' Records Division One 1890/91 to 1938/39 | publisher = Tony Brown | year = 2007 | location = Beeston, Nottingham  | isbn = 978-1-899468-66-9}}</ref> and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].<ref name = \"smith\">{{harv|Smith|2013|p=196}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n;Dumbarton<ref>{{cite book | last = Litster | first = John | title = Record of Pre-War Scottish League Players | publisher = PM Publications | location = Norwich}}</ref>\n* Scottish League: Champions [[1890\u201391 Scottish Football League|1890-1891]] and [[1891-92 Scottish Football League|1891-1892]]\n* Scottish Cup: Runners Up [[1886-87 Scottish Cup|1886-1887]];[[1890-91 Scottish Cup|1890-1891]]\n* Dumbartonshire Cup: Winners [[1888\u201389 in Scottish football|1888-1889]], [[1889\u201390 in Scottish football|1889-1890]], [[1890\u201391 in Scottish football|1890-1891]], [[1892\u201393 in Scottish football|1892-1893]] and [[1893\u201394 in Scottish football|1893\u201394]]\n* League Charity Cup: Winners 1890-91\n* Greenock Charity Cup: Winners 1889-90 - Runners Up 1888-1889\n* 1 [[cap (sport)|cap]] for Scotland in 1887\n* 1 [[cap (sport)|cap]] for the Scottish League in 1894\n* 11 representative caps for Dumbartonshire between 1885 and 1893, scoring 3 goals\n* 1 international trial match for Scotland in 1892.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book | ref = harv | last=Smith | first=Paul |title=Scotland Who's Who | publisher=Pitch Publishing | year=2013 | isbn=9781909178847 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{SFA profile}}\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/thomasmcmillan.html London Hearts profile (Scotland)]\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/thomasmcmillan.html London Hearts profile (Scottish League)]\n*[http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=5131 Tom McMillan (The Sons Archive - Dumbarton Football Club History)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMillan, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Thomas McMillan (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas McMillan}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|        name = Thomas McMillan\n|       image = \n|    fullname = Thomas McMillan\n|  birth_date = 11 October 1866\n| birth_place = [[Mauchline]], [[Scotland]]\n|  death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1928|01|02|1866|10|11}}\n|      height = \n|    position = \n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =   [[Mauchline F.C.|Mauchline]]\n| years1 =  1884\u20131885\n| years2 =  1885\u20131895\n| clubs1 =  Dumbarton Athletic\n| clubs2 =  [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]<ref>{{cite book | last = McAllister | first = Jim | title = The Sons of the Rock \u2013 The Official History of Dumbarton Football Club | publisher = J&J Robertson Printers | year = 2002 | location = Dumbarton}}</ref>\n| caps1 =             \n| caps2 =             \n| caps3 =  71 \n| goals1 =   \n| goals2 =   \n| goals3 =  4\n| nationalyears1= 1887\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1= 0\n| nationalyears2= 1894\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2= 0}}\n\n'''Thomas McMillan''' (11 October 1866 \u2013 2 January 1928) was a Scottish [[association football|footballer]].\n\n==Career==\nMcMillan played for [[Mauchline F.C.|Mauchline]], Dumbarton Athletic, [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Emms | first1 = Steve | last2 = Wells |first2 = Richard | title = Scottish League Players' Records Division One 1890/91 to 1938/39 | publisher = Tony Brown | year = 2007 | location = Beeston, Nottingham  | isbn = 978-1-899468-66-9}}</ref> and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].<ref name = \"smith\">{{harv|Smith|2013|p=196}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n;Dumbarton<ref>{{cite book | last = Litster | first = John | title = Record of Pre-War Scottish League Players | publisher = PM Publications | location = Norwich}}</ref>\n* Scottish League: Champions [[1890\u201391 Scottish Football League|1890-1891]] and [[1891-92 Scottish Football League|1891-1892]]\n* Scottish Cup: Runners Up [[1886-87 Scottish Cup|1886-1887]];[[1890-91 Scottish Cup|1890-1891]]\n* Dumbartonshire Cup: Winners [[1888\u201389 in Scottish football|1888-1889]], [[1889\u201390 in Scottish football|1889-1890]], [[1890\u201391 in Scottish football|1890-1891]], [[1892\u201393 in Scottish football|1892-1893]] and [[1893&ndash;94 in Scottish football|1893&ndash;94]]\n* League Charity Cup: Winners 1890-91\n* Greenock Charity Cup: Winners 1889-90 - Runners Up 1888-1889\n* 1 [[cap (sport)|cap]] for Scotland in 1887\n* 1 [[cap (sport)|cap]] for the Scottish League in 1894\n* 11 representative caps for Dumbartonshire between 1885 and 1893, scoring 3 goals\n* 1 international trial match for Scotland in 1892.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book | ref = harv | last=Smith | first=Paul |title=Scotland Who's Who | publisher=Pitch Publishing | year=2013 | isbn=9781909178847 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{SFA profile}}\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/thomasmcmillan.html London Hearts profile (Scotland)]\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/thomasmcmillan.html London Hearts profile (Scottish League)]\n*[http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=5131 Tom McMillan (The Sons Archive - Dumbarton Football Club History)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMillan, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_McMillan_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "R\u00faben Neves", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese footballer}}\n{{Distinguish|R\u00faben Shizenhouser Neves (footballer, born 1991)}}\n{{Portuguese name|da Silva|Neves}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = R\u00faben Neves\n| image = DK-Porto15 (4).jpg\n| image_size = \n| upright = 0.9\n| caption = Neves playing for [[FC Porto|Porto]] in 2015\n| fullname = R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|3|13|df=y}}<ref name=SW/>\n| birth_place = [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)|Mozelos]], Portugal\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}<ref name=FPFprofile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132014\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs2 = \u2192 [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] (loan)\n| years1 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| caps1 = 59\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| caps2 = 106\n| goals2 = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u20132014\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 31\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2014\u20132017\n| nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 23\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| nationalyears5 = 2016\n| nationalteam5 = [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 1\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| nationalyears6 = 2015\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 13\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| club-update = 16:19, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:50, 10 September 2019 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|POR}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|Runner-up|[[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 Czech Republic]]|}}\n}}\n'''R\u00faben Diogo da Silva Neves''' ({{IPA-pt|n\u025bv\u0283|eu}}; born 13 March 1997) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Porto===\nBorn in [[Mozelos (Santa Maria da Feira)]], [[Aveiro District]], Neves grew up supporting [[FC Porto]] and joined the club's youth system at the age of 8.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/21/ruben-neves-diogo-jota-wolves-porto-cricket-interview|title=Wolves\u2019 R\u00faben Neves and Diogo Jota: \u2018Porto has wine, food but here it\u2019s fine\u2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Stuart|last=James|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=PortuGoal>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/on-the-rise/356-profile-of-porto-prodigy-ruben-neves|title=Profile of Porto prodigy R\u00faben Neves|publisher=PortuGOAL|date=24 December 2015|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> During his time with the academy, he also spent a season on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Padroense F.C.|Padroense]] which acted as the under-16 side;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2132818.html|title=The rapid rise of R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|last=Pimentel|first=Jos\u00e9 Nuno|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=17 August 2014}}</ref> on his time in the youth structures, [[FC Porto B|reserve team]] manager [[Lu\u00eds Castro (Portuguese footballer)|Lu\u00eds Castro]] described him as a player with \"extraordinary mental qualities, to go along with technical and tactical skills\".<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nAhead of the [[2014\u201315 Primeira Liga|2014\u201315 campaign]], Neves was earmarked to bypass Porto's under-19s and play with the reserves instead. Following an injury to teammate [[Mikel Agu]], however, he was called by [[Julen Lopetegui]] to be part of the main squad's pre-season preparations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-tem-um-talento-mental-extraordinario-4070889.html|title=R\u00faben Neves tem um talento mental extraordin\u00e1rio|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves has an extraordinary mental talent|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> On 15 August 2014, aged 17 years and five months, he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut where he started and scored in a 2\u20130 home win against [[C.S. Mar\u00edtimo|Mar\u00edtimo]] \u2013 in doing so, he became the youngest player in the club's history to score a goal in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-fc-porto-maritimo-cronica/53ee72880cf2c1dfdf15bb68.html|title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=FC Porto-Mar\u00edtimo, 2\u20130 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Almeida|first=Germano|language=pt|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> He played his first match in the [[UEFA Champions League]] five days later in a 1\u20130 win over [[Lille OSC|Lille]], and broke another record (previously held by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]) by being the youngest Portuguese to appear in the tournament.<ref name=PortuGoal/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-campeoes-fc-porto-ruben-neves-cristiano-ronaldo-lille-play-off/53f4eee90cf2103fd4482b11.html|title=R\u00faben Neves o portugu\u00eas mais novo de sempre a jogar na ''Champions''|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves the youngest Portuguese ever to play in the Champions|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2014, during a [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage]] fixture against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]], Neves suffered an injury to his right knee following a collision in midfield with [[Alex Teixeira]]. At the end of the game, the club explained that he suffered a sprain, with apparent damage to the internal lateral ligament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-com-lesao-no-joelho-direito-4288722.html|title=R\u00faben Neves com les\u00e3o no joelho direito|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves with right knee injury|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> After spending nearly a month on the sidelines, he returned to the pitch in a [[2014\u201315 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|3\u20131 home win]] over [[C.F. Uni\u00e3o|Uni\u00e3o da Madeira]] in the [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/ruben-neves-regressa-aos-convocados-924835.html|title=R\u00faben Neves regressa aos convocados|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves returns to squad|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> following his injury, his role in midfield was filled by [[Casemiro]] and he spent the majority of the remainder of the season behind the Brazilian in the pecking order.<ref name=PortuGoal/>\n\nOn 20 October 2015, aged 18 years and 221 days, Neves became the youngest player to start as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] in the Champions League, helping Porto to a 2\u20130 win against [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] in [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|the group phase]] and surpassing previous record holder [[Rafael van der Vaart]], who held it since 16 September 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2296033.html|title=Porto's R\u00faben Neves, Iker Casillas make history|publisher=UEFA|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> On 5 December, in a 2\u20131 success over [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira|Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira]] also at the [[Est\u00e1dio do Drag\u00e3o]], he broke another record by becoming the youngest player to achieve 50 games for the club, surpassing players like [[Fernando Gomes (footballer)|Fernando Gomes]] and [[Jaime Magalh\u00e3es]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/ruben-neves-e-o-mais-jovem-a-completar-50-jogos-4917762.html|title=R\u00faben Neves \u00e9 o mais jovem a completar 50 jogos|trans-title=R\u00faben Neves is the youngest to complete 50 games|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=6 December 2015|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves scored his second competitive goal on 3 February 2016, opening the scoreline in a 3\u20130 triumph at [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]] for [[2015\u201316 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|the semi-finals]] of the [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/nunca-e-facil-mudar-de-estrategia-5014013.html|title=Nunca \u00e9 f\u00e1cil mudar de estrat\u00e9gia|trans-title=\"It is never easy to change strategy\"|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=3 February 2016|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\nOn 8 July 2017, [[EFL Championship]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] announced that they had signed Neves for an undisclosed fee, thought to be in the region of \u00a315.8 million \u2013 a club and league record fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20170708-neves-arrives/|title=Neves arrives!|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=8 July 2017|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Upon joining, he was reunited with former Porto manager [[Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo]].<ref name=Fifty>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20181010-50-games-of-neves-a-look-back/|title=50 games of Neves: A look back|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C|date=10 October 2018|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 15 August, in a 3\u20132 away win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40858331|title=Hull City 2\u20133 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Neves was nominated for the EFL Championship Player of the Season and Young Player of the Season awards, and was also included in the Team of the Season along with teammates [[Conor Coady]] and [[John Ruddy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43641225|title=EFL awards: Tom Cairney, Ruben Neves & Ryan Sessgenon on Championship shortlist|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> His team was ultimately [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|promoted as champions]] with the player scoring six goals in 42 appearances, all of which were scored from outside of the box;<ref name=PR>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/everton-wolves-richarlison-ruben-neves-goals-report-a8488566.html|title=Richarlison and Ruben Neves ready to lead by example for Everton and Wolves|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Nash|first=Tim|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/693584|title=FPL promotion prospects: The Wolves worth hunting|publisher=[[Premier League]]|date=27 May 2018|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> at the conclusion of the campaign, he claimed a hat-trick of club awards as he walked away with the Player of the Season, Player's Player of the Season and Goal of the Season accolades.<ref name=Fifty/> On 7 April 2019 it was also announced that Neves had been awarded the EFL Goal of the Year award (for 2018) for his goal against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/04/08/ruben-neves-volley-earns-efl-goal-of-the-year-award/|title=Ruben Neves volley earns EFL Goal of the Year award|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|last=Hatfield|first=Luke|date=8 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nWolves announced that Neves had signed a new contract in July 2018, extending until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44689010|title=Ruben Neves: Wolves midfielder signs new five-year deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> In the first match of [[2018\u201319 Premier League|the new season]], he scored his first [[Premier League]] goal and assisted [[Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez]] in the latter's competitive debut, as his team twice came from behind to draw 2\u20132 against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/11/wolves-everton-premier-league-match-report|title=Wolves\u2019 Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez pegs back 10-man Everton after Richarlison's double|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Aarons|first=Ed|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|title=Wolves 2 Everton 2: Jimenez header ensures Richarlison's brace in vain|publisher=[[FourFourTwo]]|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=11 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811232148/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/news/wolves-2-everton-2-jimenez-header-ensures-richarlisons-brace-vain|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> His appearance in the match, alongside compatriots [[Rui Patr\u00edcio]], [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]], [[Diogo Jota]] and [[H\u00e9lder Costa (footballer)|H\u00e9lder Costa]] also saw the club break the league record for the most Portuguese players named in a starting line-up.<ref name=PR/>\n\nOn 6 October 2018, Neves made his 50th appearance for Wolverhampton and marked the occasion by contributing in the build-up for [[Matt Doherty (footballer, born 1992)|Matt Doherty]]'s winning goal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref name=Fifty/> The following January, his 55th-minute winning goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] in the [[FA Cup]], \"a venomous dipping shot from {{convert|31|yards|m|abbr=out}} that beat [[Simon Mignolet]] at his near post\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46718633|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 2\u20131 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Chowdhury|first=Saj|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref> was voted the best of [[2018\u201319 FA Cup#Third Round Proper|the third round]] by visitors to [[BBC Sport]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46788650|title=FA Cup: Wolves midfielder Ruben Neves wins goal of the FA Cup third round|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2019, Neves was made Wolves' club captain for the first time, when he led the team in the absence of regular skipper [[Conor Coady]] as Wolves secured progression to the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup]] Fourth Round with a penalty shoot-out victory over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at Molineux in the clubs' Third Round fixture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballfancast.com/premier-league/wolves/wolves-ruben-neves-posts-on-twitter-after-captaining-the-club-for-the-first-time|title=Wolves\u2019 Ruben Neves posts on Twitter after captaining the club for the first time|publisher=www.footballfancast.com|date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Ruben Neves avec la selection.jpg|thumb|upright|Neves playing for [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] in 2014]]Neves represented [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal]] at the [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], helping the country reach the semi-finals as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. For his performances, he was named among the top ten talents of the tournament by a selection of [[UEFA]] reporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/news/newsid=2106764.html|title=Ten under-17 players to keep an eye on|publisher=UEFA|date=22 May 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, still aged 17, Neves was called by coach [[Rui Jorge]] to be part of the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/euro_sub_21/artigo/2014/08/29/portugal-sub-21-sporting-domina-convocat-ria-ruben-neves-chamado|title=Sporting domina convocat\u00f3ria, Ruben Neves chamado|trans-title=Sporting dominate list, Ruben Neves called|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 14 October, helping to a 5\u20134 home win against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] for [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|the playoff round]] of the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000413/match=2015238/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Portugal through after nine-goal thriller|publisher=UEFA|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen the finals began in the Czech Republic, Neves broke a new record by becoming the youngest player to debut for the Portuguese under-21s in the tournament, aged 18 years and three months, playing five minutes to help beat [[England national under-21 football team|England]] 1\u20130 in the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Group B|group stage]] opener.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/seleccao/portugal/artigo/2015/06/19/ruben-neves-quebra-recorde-mas-quer-mais-nao-posso-abrandar|title=R\u00faben Neves quebra recorde mas quer mais: \"N\u00e3o posso abrandar\"|trans-title=Ruben Neves breaks record but wants more: \"I can't slow down\"|publisher=SAPO|language=pt|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> It was his only appearance, as the country reached [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|the final]] and lost it to [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000411/match=2015383/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Spot-on Sweden beat Portugal to win U21 EURO|publisher=UEFA|last=Kell|first=Tom|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nNeves was first called up to [[Portugal national football team|the senior squad]] on 10 November 2015, ahead of [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] as an injury replacement for [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/618334/Liverpool-Chelsea-Ruben-Neves-Porto-international-debut-Portugal|title=Liverpool and Chelsea target in high demand as youngster set to make international debut|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|last=Gray|first=James|date=10 November 2015|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in the former match, featuring 17 minutes in the 0\u20131 loss in [[Krasnodar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/news/newsid=2304930.html|title=R\u00fassia vence Portugal em Krasnodar|trans-title=Russia beat Portugal in Krasnodar|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=14 November 2015|accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref> then played the entire 2\u20130 win against the latter at the [[Stade Josy Barthel]], sharing the midfield area with Porto teammates [[Danilo Pereira (Portuguese footballer)|Danilo Pereira]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Andr\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao/andre-andre/luxemburgo-portugal-2-0-cronica|title=Luxemburgo-Portugal, 0\u20132 (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=Luxembourg-Portugal, 0\u20132 (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/selecao/noticias/interior/aproveitamos-o-meiocampo-do-fc-porto-4889964.html|title=Aproveitamos o meio-campo do FC Porto|trans-title=We took advantage of the FC Porto midfield|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=17 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves was selected by full side manager [[Fernando Santos (Portuguese footballer)|Fernando Santos]] to a preliminary 35-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad \u2013 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced?|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> but he did not make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/portugal-world-cup-squad|title=Nearly half Portugal's Euro squad to miss World Cup|publisher=[[Special Broadcasting Service]]|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]] on home soil, Neves played in the 3\u20131 semi-final win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], but was dropped from the starting eleven for the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Final|final]] against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] for the more defensive Danilo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Danilo replaces Neves for Portugal in Nations League final |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/09/danilo-replaces-neves-for-portugal-in-nations-league-final |accessdate=16 August 2019 |publisher=Euronews |date=9 June 2019}}</ref> In that match at his former club ground the ''Drag\u00e3o'', he came on in added time for [[William Carvalho]] as the Portuguese won 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portugal 1&ndash;0 The Netherlands |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jun/09/portugal-v-netherlands-nations-league-final-live |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAn article on [[UEFA|UEFA.com]] described Neves as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] who is not afraid to go forward and prompt attacks, showing great maturity combined with an accurate passing skill, great vision and an astute sense of positioning. His playing attributes also granted him comparisons to Portuguese international teammate Moutinho for his fine first touch, similar desire to press his opponents and excellent distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=por/news/newsid=2241045.html|title=UEFA.com's weekly wonderkid: R\u00faben Neves|publisher=UEFA|date=2 May 2015|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nNeves also drew praise in the media for his technical, tactical and mental qualities,<ref name=PortuGoal/> as well as his intelligence and long-range shooting ability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/the-portuguese-star-who-broke-the-records-of-ronaldo-ready-to-jo-72883|title=The Portuguese star who broke the records of Ronaldo ready to join Juventus|publisher=Calcio Mercato|last=Laurenti|first=Mirko|date=23 November 2018|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{